natural problem: The function $f(x)$ is defined by $f(x)=x^{2}-x$. What is the value of $f(4)$?

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall>x. f x = x powr 2 - x"
shows  "f 4 = 12"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 The function $f(x)$ is defined by $f(x)=x^{2}-x$. What is the value of $f(4)$? The final Answer is 12
 ### Proof
 $f(4)=4^2-4=16-4=\boxed{12}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes x f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall>x. f x = x powr 2 - x"
shows  "f 4 = 12"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Find the value of the function $f(x) = x^2 - x$ when $x = 4$.
